observations.recommendation:
We have recommended the Municipal Mayor to direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that relevant information is supplied and made available to the intended users of the Financial Statements, enabling them to make well-informed decisions based on a comprehensive understanding of the financial reports. Disclosures should be made, but not limited to the following:
amount and nature of the cash and cash equivalents in Note 5;
Biological Assets in compliance with IPSAS 27;
additional disclosure on the status of one-time cleansing of the Municipality in compliance with COA Circular No. 2020-006; and
financial liabilities, specifically the nature, character, composition/ breakdown, and date of incurrence of Accounts Payable and the disaggregated balances of the Deferred Real Property Tax and Special Education Tax (RPT/SET) Income Accounts to show the attributable amounts for taxpayers' advance payments, the accrued amount for the current year 2024, and the amount representing delinquencies.

We have recommended the Municipal Mayor to instruct the Municipal Assessor to:
Assist the Municipality to document the legality of ownership of the lots through a Transfer Certificate of Title in the name of the Municipality as required under Sec. 39 (2) of PD No. 1445 and Section 148 of COA Circular No. 92-386;
Request from his provincial counterpart to appraise the properties without assigned costs so that these could be recorded properly in the books of accounts of the municipality to fairly present the Land account in the financial statements.

We have recommended the Municipal Mayor in coordination with the Human Resource Office to:
Revisit and study the organizational structure of the Municipality, particularly the staffing pattern of all its offices, and consider abolishing items that are not regarded as vital, specifically those that have been left vacant for an extended period;
Fill up all vacant positions that are still considered vital by hiring new employees or expediting the promotion of deserving employees;
Devise a mechanism to also provide equal permanent job opportunities to the personnel under JOC/COS status; and
Consider institutionalizing Review Programs for JOC/COS workers so they can be empowered and encouraged to take the Civil Service Exam to earn the required eligibility to be permanent employees.

In view of the foregoing we have recommended the following:
Require the Municipal Accountant to identify the existence of the Registry of Public Infrastructure which includes all local road networks implemented by the Municipality prior to the implementation of IPSAS;
Create an Inventory Committee who shall be responsible in the conduct of physical inventory of local road networks funded by the Municipality;
Require Municipal Engineer to prepare a list of road inventory and its vicinity map for easy identification during and after the physical inventory and;
d.   Ensure that road components (road lot, pavements, drainage and slope, etc.) are indicated in the road network ledger and property cards maintained by the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Engineer.

Recommendation:
With the foregoing observations cited above, we have recommended the following routines/procedures to be observed by the Municipal Treasury:
Consistently deposit daily and intact all the collections to the authorized depository bank;
Conduct detailed and systematic verification of collections reported by the collecting officers;
Direct the Liquidating Officer to discontinue from paying claims of employees and encashment of private checks out of collections;
Instruct all the collecting officers as well as the Liquidating Officer to completely and properly accomplish the Report of Collections and Deposits (RCD);
Instruct the collector concerned to explain in writing why there are erasures/alterations on the dates of the duplicate ORs;
Assign a person who will monitor the requisition, receipt and distribution of accountable forms;
7.    Institute appropriate action against the erring accountable officer/s for non-remittance of his/her collections to the Liquidating Officer.
